{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"046f9879-83de-4fc8-bc50-862e9ba05729","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>()` (MSTest v2+) instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n}\n```\n\n**Why this is better:**\n\n- Pinpoints *which line* should throw — `[ExpectedException]` passes even if the constructor throws instead\n- You can capture the exception to assert on its message/properties\n- No risk of false positives from setup code\n\nFor async methods, use `Assert.ThrowsExceptionAsync<T>()`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"661395d7-9692-42d7-be62-5527853a43e3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to modernize a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a straightforward knowledge question - I don't need to use any tools.\n\nThe modern approach is to use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>()` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>()` (xUnit/NUnit) instead of the `[ExpectedException]` attribute.","outputTokens":278,"requestId":"BC28:26D998:1D754E8:20AE59C:69FA9657"},"id":"3cbb7631-4340-4ad9-8ee7-21cec5c75270","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:16:15.933Z","parentId":"be2f0667-2dd7-494c-a2f3-aa1f3b36824d"}
